Although the scone was delicious, the espresso (which I love, love love) was not made properly and had this slight, odd aftertaste which I could quite tell was the result of not cleaning the machine or from some kind of chemical residue from cleaning. Either way, I've had better.

What makes them appealing (if you're not super concerned about how your coffee actually tastes) is their seating area. It's bright, cheerful, clean and quiet. This may not be an accurate representation of a Sunday afternoon, but when I was there, there were people outside, but only one other in the seating area (which is a separate room and therefore away from the sound of espresso/cappuccino/work-related noises) and I thought - Man! This would be an awesome place to read the paper or a novel or do some writing. 

If I were basing my review solely on service and product, it'd get two-stars, but I'm giving it a bump because quiet, comfortable coffee-shop space is highly coveted real estate in my book.

Old City Coffee roasts its own beans and on that alone, I'd give it 5 stars. There are bins at the front with the date when they were roasted and there's a blend for every taste. My personal favorite is the Balzac Blend. They have specials every couple of weeks. 

When it comes to a cafe, though, that's where Old City Coffee fails. It's on a beautiful little cobblestone street in Old City just a stone's throw from Christ Church. It has a cute seating area with french doors and a couple of tables outside if the weather's nice. Sadly, though their hot coffee always seems oddly bitter to me and I can't figure out why since I know the beans they roast make good coffee. It's so weird, or maybe it's just my taste buds don't work at this exact longitude and latitude. 

When it comes to the food, though, I have yet to have something I like. I love biscotti so I bought one of theirs and not only was it the size of my arm, it was nearly impossible to bite into. The cookies are huge but tasteless and the muffins also huge but have a strange crumbly texture that has you anxiously trying to get a secure bite. I like my food smaller and of better quality. Huge does not equal good.

Service is spotty.

They do take credit cards, though, and I like the shakes in the summer, but as a hangout, I can't get into this place.

I plan to update this review once I am off of my juice cleanse and can have a nice cup of coffee however I went here this morning and was taken aback by the decor.  I have to admit, I am a snob when it comes to ambiance.  I think it is JUST as important as the actual quality of the food/drink- it can take away the value of the experience JUST as much as it can add to it.  I came here with my business partners and was surprised because I was expecting so much more due to the yelp reviews.  This very same feeling has happened at least once other time this week to me when I was expecting something SO MUCH better than what I saw.  I only had a hot water with lemon but my partners had coffees and iced coffees respectively.  They enjoyed it without so much word about it (they are not fanatics such as I am) but I have certainly bookmarked the location to return so I can share in their "delightful roasts" (as I hear on the reviews).  If I were to rate it on the decor and ambiance, it would stay low- even 2 stars- it is tight and cramped and the seating adjacent to the ordering area is limited and unimpressive.  Sorry- I know there are a lot of Old City Coffee die hards out there but like I said, I will update once I try my first sip of coffee, i promise!

I would like to rename this place "good, but grumpy" coffee.  I really love the strong coffee and sweet treats the Old City spot offers, the side street offers a quiet refuge from the hustle of old city.  However, why do the Batista's always seem to put out?  We do have to fill our own cups... they merely slap down the requested size and bark out the bill.   And if you ask for a treat behind the counter, or even a lb of coffee, get ready for the cold shoulder of quiet annoyance.  Stay away from the overpriced oatmeal (gross) but be sure to try one of the baked goods from the jars.  They make most of the treats on site and they are delicious.  If you are feeling brash, ask one of the baristas for the freshest batch.  I, for one, will keep coming back for the coffee and cookies, but will spend time wishing the service was friendlier.

Whenever it gets chilly outside, and I just want to stay in bed instead of riding my bike in the freezing cold to work, I savor my breakfasts a little more.  I skip the green smoothie and plunge into that carb coma...

Well, I go here for that.  They serve this wonderfully delicious thing called a Nuffin, a muffin made with no sugar, fruit and oats.  I normally don't eat heavy foods, but I really like this thing.  I think it's low-fat too!  Anyway, they have various flavors, and it really hits the spot... and gives me a carb coma.  That's why I don't eat many ... but after I eat one, even half of it, I feel my brain going into a fog, like I'm back in my warm cozy bed, so that's a nice feeling.  Except then I have to work - uh oh!  It's an indulgence that I can enjoy for breakfast, however, so that's why I love them.

Their freshly-roasted beans are really amazing too- they have one blend that just took my breath away - pricey, but delicious...a real treat.  I usually buy these for special dining occasions at home since they are so good.

Their brewed coffee?  I haven't had the pleasure of a decent cup in a long time, now, so I can't recommend it.  Missing the rich roundness  I identify their establishment with... maybe it's just personal taste.  Maybe they use a lighter roast, I don't know.

But I did like their set-up there, and love the space - early in the morning, it's bright, clean - shared newspapers to read and a nice big window opening onto the street.  I've always had nice service with a smile.

Oh, and they never use meat at the cafe.

This is where I get my coffee almost every day while at work (I work on 3rd & Race in the TLA Entertainment offices.) So I have pretty regular experience with them, both purchasing drinks directly and individual drinks.

The basic rundown is that the quality of the coffee beans are by far above average. And the iced coffee is a demonic broth that will make you feel like you just injected rocket fuel directly into your veins. (Your stomach may quickly alleviate you of that feeling, if you suffer from reflux.) After talking to one of the Barrista's about this - I suggested they were slipping crack cocaine in there - she said that the iced coffee is a mixture of all the roasts of the day, brewed double strength. So, there you go. Douse it with liquid sugar and a healthy amount of milk to cut the acid, and expect to get a lot of design and coding done before you crash and want to sleep under your desk for a week.  

They also have something called Balzac's blend here that is quite good. If you've ever read Balzac's humorous and incredibly verbose essay on the benefits of coffee, well... Yeah. It is well named.

I wouldn't suggest going here for bulk tea though. Though the tea quality is fairly high it is apparent that they don't sell much of it- every time I've bought it it has been fairly stale. I suggest Remedy tea on Samson between 16th and 17th. Review of Remedy coming up in a bit.

Husband and I are coffee fiends.  We love coffee.  We drink it all the time.  We have an espresso machine on the kitchen counter so we can satisfy the coffee urge whenever.  Oh, but we don't patronize Satrbucks.  I can't bring myself to do it.  There's one literally on every corner, and I think I'm afraid they're trying to take over the world.  I just can't bring myself to drop money in there, and they certainly don't need my dimes to stay afloat.

This presents a dilemma on occasion when husband and I are the road and out of our element.  We know the great little coffee shops in our 'hood, but elsewhere we're lost.  So we were really happy one sunny afternoon after a visit to the beautiful grounds of Christ Church to literally stumble on Old City Coffee.  It's totally out of the way and tucked on a side street off Market, and I'm not sure we ever would have visited otherwise.

But.  The interior was so darn cute -- minimalist and all about coffee, with barrels of beans ready for you to select -- and the coffee was so darn good that we came back again and again.  The coffee was ground and then brewed right before our eyes, served piping hot, and was STRONG.  Yessss.  We were really happy with our experience!  Even picked up some airtight glass jars to store our beans and grounds at home.

This place is so great. I'm delighted to pay $3 for an iced here when it means:

- Staff offer me fresh lemon slices to go with it
- I get a free wifi login (3 hours' use) with purchase
- The seating area is pleasant and comfortable to work in  (well-lit and protected from foot traffic so you don't have to worry about leaving your bag 
- The bathroom is clean and easy to get to
- Almost every table is near a power outlet
- They serve Bassett's ice cream (yummm) and Pequea Valley Yogurt (high-fat but local and SO delicious!)

Plus, it's only 2 blocks from the Arden Theatre - perfect to stop in before/after a matinee or (if you have kids) a weekend workshop.

I can't vouch for the baked goods -- my companion had a brownie and said it was "fine." But the milkshake was amazing, and the bagel with peanut butter was good too.

Pretty much the only downers: Wifi can be a bit slow, and occasionally some salesman decides this is the perfect location to shout at a would-be customer in a vain attempt to pitch him during a "sales meeting" in the seating area. Thank goodness they left after 15 min, because even with my headphones in, the lack of carpeting meant that his booming voice was bouncing off the walls like crazy. But I really can't blame the coffeeshop for their customers!

Are you kidding? 
     Who could give old city coffee anything less than 5 stars?  Communists!  That's who!!   If they had six stars, I would give seven.  Let me list the reason this is the greatest coffee on the planet

1, Coffee!!!   Excellent, HOT, STRONG, perfect flavor every time.  I don't know about you, but I like my coffee really hot.  I am not sure, but it would not surprise me if they have a small thermonuclear reactor going under those boilers.  Oh, don't like hot.... HOW BOUT THE ICED!!  It's excellent.  

2, Food.  Excellent.  Their Jewish apple cake is the best ever.  Hands down.  They also have excellent salads, soup, and seasonal items like the butternut squash soup.  Wow, that great.  

3. People.  The service is always friendly.  The people always seem happy to be there.  

4. Location.  Now, this is the key for me.  My brother and I were walking 12 years ago when I was helping him move into old town and we walked down this perfect Philly Street only to SMELL the coffee.  The street is like a post card and if you're lucky you can sit outside on a fall day and enjoy your coffee on their tables.  If not, shuffle down to the dog park on one of those benches.  The inside has plenty of seating and it's always clean.  

So, there you have it.  If it sounds like I love the place, it's because I do and I will make a habit of stopping there whenever I am up from DC. 

Oh, one thing, you guys have to put the "WALL OF FAME" up.  If you're reading this Old City, you know what I am talking about

ScottG.

UPDATE
The wall of fame is back!!!   Just when you think this place cannot get any getter, it does.  WAY TO GO OLD CITY.

I work across the alley from Old City Coffee and usually come here multiple times per week, and I've been buying their beans to brew at home for years. The coffee here is strong and dark and fairly priced. My personal coffee standards are probably a little too high as a result of my frequent patronage, and very few places can really compare.

I like being able to pour my own coffee, although I do wish the various fixings were a little easier to get to (especially as a short person with short arms). Particularly when it's busy, I struggle a bit to reach the stirrers and sleeves, and I often end up reaching over people uncomfortably and feeling in the way while adding my sugar and half&half.

When I feel like treating myself to breakfast, a toasted everything bagel with cream cheese is my go-to. The huge cookies in the jars by the window are delicious. I've also gotten muffins a couple times and they've been quite good.

I alternate between the Reading and Old City blends for home use, and also like the San Francisco blend (even darker), which I can only seem to find at the RTM location now. If you have a coffee club card, you get a free pound after you buy 10, which is totally awesome.

i recently visited philadelphia and was in need of a caffeine boost before a very busy day of meetings.  i used my handy yelp iphone app to search for nearby coffee shops.  luckily, i was directed to old city coffee.  

this quaint little shop is tucked away on a side street between 2nd and 3rd st.  i arrived around 7.30 am to find a short line and two very industrious baristas.  after about a 2 minute wait, i was able to order my 3 shot medium iced latte. 

i am a HUGE coffee snob and hate burned and ill-timed espresso shots.  more often than not, i'm dissatisfied with the final product at most coffee shops i visit.  however, by the fate of the gods, my barista made THE BEST latte i've had since i visited seattle about 2 months ago.  really.  i didn't taste the unpleasant acrid burn of badly pulled espresso.  

in addition to the coffee menu, there are some pre-packaged salads and sandwiches.  also available are freshly baked pastries.  unfortunately, i am gluten-intolerant so i couldn't indulge, but the muffins did look delicious.  

probable con: this place could feel cramped quickly if more than about 8 customers was present at any given time.

This is my favorite coffee shop in Philly, and that's saying something.

The coffee itself is phenomenal. In a crowded market of small-batch roasters, these guys stand out. All the roasts tend towards the darker side, and have a smooth, rich flavor profile. The coffees are lower in acidity and fuller in body than local competitors like Reanimator, which is a plus to me. Old City is the only coffee I drink at home, and the price on whole beans is very reasonable for coffee of this quality. I particularly love and recommend the Balzac Blend.

I haven't tried much of their food, but their muffins and scones are excellent. Lunch fare is on the much lighter side, which won't do it for a hungry man like me. I mostly just come for the coffee.

The shop itself is cozy and well-lit, and modern without being pretentious. All the staff are super friendly. I really like the laid-back vibe in here - there's none of the attitude you'll get at some other coffee shops (looking at you, Menagerie). I work in the neighborhood, and relish my afternoon walks to Old City Coffee. Old City is bursting at the seams with cute coffee shops, and this is the best one.

I liked this place much more before the move.  The atmosphere has taken a big hit, but I understand that- it would be very hard to match the charm of the former location.  What really bothers me is the service I have experienced on my recent visits.  What I really used to like about this place was the friendly and accommodating baristas.  The service seems much more like a fast food chain now.  To give an example- the last time I was there I tried to order a 1/2 coffee, 1/2 hot chocolate.  They serve both items and I do not think this is an unreasonable request.  And if the price difference were a problem, I would have been happy to pay the higher price of a full hot chocolate, I'm used to doing that most places.  But instead the server informed me that I actually wanted a mocha.  I told her that I really just want house coffee mixed with hot chocolate.  She replied that my request and a mocha are "exactly the same thing".  Obviously this is not true at all, but after repeating myself once more with no luck I decided to just go with it and said OK.  When she called my name I found that my mug contained a shot of espresso at the bottom of a pile of airy milk foam topped with a sickening amount of chocolate syrup.  The drink weighed about 2 ounces and tasted like I was drinking hersheys' syrup out of the bottle.  And it cost 4.25$!!  What an utter disappointment.  Form now on it's L'Aube for me.  17th and Wallace- I highly recommend it.

I took my friends to mugshots Sunday morning for a quick breakfast before my friend from out of town had to catch her train home. I ordered the Mango Mamma Smoothie and my friend ordered the Strawberry Banana smoothie. The line was moving incredibly slow but we waited it out (staying positive!). We finally got to the register after waiting 15 minutes and we were greeted very coldly. I immediately felt as if I should apologize to HER for the inconvenience. After we ordered we waited another 25 minutes for the girl "making" the coffee and smoothies to call out the names of two smoothies (one being the mango mamma). She placed them on the counter, I picked up the mango mamma and a guy told me it was his. I apologized and gave it to him. The girl then looked at me and in a very disrespectful manner said " YES. Those smoothies go together that's why I put them together." 10 more minutes went by, at this point my friend and I tried to get our money back but the CHEERY register girl completely ignored us. The coffee/smoothie "maker" continued to make coffee for the customers who were 2/3 people behind us in line. She finally put one mango mamma out and then said there was a strawberry banana for "Mimi" (not my friend's name). A man took that one and I took mine. My friend decided she would rather pay 100 dollars for 10 Invisible smoothies than have to talk to one of the lovely employees again so she cut her loses and left.

Dear Mugshots,

I consider you a necessary evil.  I recognize that some of my friends might like to go to your establishment to study.  I want you to know that every time I come to your store, I die a little inside.

The coffee is not great, but lord knows you charge a pretty penny for it.  Your service, while improved since you moved from 21st and Fairmount, can still be spotty.  The tables are too small and the space is way too cramped.  So even if I make plans to meet someone there, it's a crapshoot as to whether we will even find reasonable seating.  

Your food is generally horrible.  Your vegan cowgirl cookie is truly inedible.  Cardboard would taste better and at least it wouldn't have calories.  One time, around 6pm on a Saturday, I tried to order a sandwich for dinner.  But apparently your kitchen closes at like, 4pm, despite the fact that you were open until 11pm that night.  Why would you do that?  I had to settle on a pathetic pre-made sandwich that lacked flavor and was soggy and depressing.

I want you to understand that even though I sometimes find myself in your store, I am still deeply depressed by the experience.   Please stop being so mediocre.  Alternatively, be mediocre and cheaper.  That is all.

With sadness,
Sharon

Five years ago mugshots was amazing. The staff was friendly and quirky, the menu was large and the food was delicious and freshly prepared and had thoughtful vegetarian/vegan options. I went here every day for a long time. 

After the move, the food is premade and reheated. I've gotten sick from it twice and had to return it once because it tasted spoiled. The reheated food usually ends up being ice cold in the middle. The staff somehow transitioned from friendly, interesting young artist types to extremely unfriendly middle aged women who rush you through your order and barely look you in the eye. The menu has far less healthy and veg friendly options.

I've never seen a business shoot themselves in the foot so completely as this one did. I was actually pleased to see the brewery town location close - the staff here was actually super friendly, but the quality of the food was even worse. I hope it will clue them in that their change in business model was an unfortunate one.

Oh Mugshots. (sad sigh) 

I used to live in the Fairmount neighborhood where this cafe resides, and was a regular at their old location at 21st & Fairmount when I could afford it ($$$). I moved out of the neighborhood but decided to give their new location a try. 

Sadly, as I suspected, things are just not the same. The new space is smaller, and lacks the crunchy, neighborhoody vibe from the old spot. I was there during a weekday around lunchtime and ordered the Machine Gun Kelly, a grilled panini-like turkey sandwich. It came out cold, I guess they only grill the bread, the cheese unmelted- and I was the only customer they were serving at the time. The guy making it seemed more concerned with getting back to his conversation at the counter with a lady friend. The food just lacked love, something I had never experienced from a Mugshots before. For far less than $7.50, I could have gotten a love-less cold sub at Wawa. 

Also, my empty plate sat at my table for a half hour and none of the three or four staff who weren't busy came around to clean up. I understand when a place is packed and they don't clean up, but my sense was the staff seemed lazy (albeit friendly). 

I gave it one last (mug) shot, but I won't be coming back here in the foreseeable future. There's too many other quality coffee shops in Philly to waste time at a sub-par establishment.

I want something in between their old location and the new one (and not geographically)...the old Fairmount location was a much more comfortable neighborhood spot: comfy couches, plenty of quiet corners, etc. The new location is much larger, louder and more rigid. The old location the food was prepared to order (it often took FOREVER) and the food was good, at the new location I ordered a sandwich and my order was called in less than 60 seconds and I was handed a cold tin-foil wrapped product (no signs indicating premade). 
Unlike other reviewers I don't think the staff is unfriendly, I DO think that the customer service is horribly unorganized (order from here, get your food over there and wait for your drinks somewhere else?). All in all the move was certainly for the worse, I'd rather wait 15 minutes for a sandwich than eat one that's been in the refrigerator all morning (or at least have a sign that says pre-made). Also, bring headphones if your trying to get work done because its much louder at the new spot.
Coffee is vey good  and smoothies are okay. The latter often feels just like juice and ice blended together though...I'll definitely be back but always left wanting more.

I wish Mugshots stayed put.

Their old location was comfy cozy...it felt like Friends or Cheers...and that's probably because I'd walk in screaming NORRRRRRRRRRRM to everybody whilst singing Smelly Cat to my cashier and pouring liquor into my coffee.

The new location is nicely furnished, but it's more a GET IN GET OUT kind of feel...hard chairs, hard benches, and not much else going on in there.  The old place had open mic nights, things that made it unique.

I stopped there for hummus on a bagel...the cheapest thing I could think of to satisfy my hunger at $2.65.  I almost stopped in the other day for an egg and cheese but $4.95 for an egg and cheese?  It's not cheap and I don't want to linger.  

I do like the local art they display...but even still the walls feel empty.  And I thought the whole premise of the name "Mugshots" was a pun for being across the street from the Penitentary.  I'd see it while passing Eastern State and just burst out laughing asking joggers if they got it...GET IT?  Now the play on words doesn't even make SENSE.  I'm not going to never return...it's close to home and convenient, I just miss the old Mugshots.

It pains me to say this, but I am now ending my several year relationship with mugshots.  I absolutely LOVE the Capone sandwich.  It was a lot easier for me to get when they had the Manayunk location, however that still didn't stop me from going out of my way at least once a month to get my fill of The Capone.  Today was my first trip to the new location.  I order the normal...the Capone on wheat bread.  I was then told they were pre made as wraps and that because the owner was there he couldn't make it as a sandwich.  A little annoyed, I took the wrap out of the cooler myself and paid the $11 for a pre made wrap and OJ.  The wrap was TERRIBLE!  How can you pre make something with fresh avocado on it, or the mayo based spread and not expect it to make the greens and wrap soggy and gross?  about half of the way through it I even found a long black hair in my wrap!!!!!!   Are you kidding me?  Went back to the counter, refused the offer of "another sandwich" and left to go home and make myself some lunch.  You will always hold a special place in my heart mugshots, but I'm afraid our time has come.

UPDATED:  I took the manager, Adam, up on his offer to meet and discuss coffee and Mugshots.  He was very informative and shared with my husband and I a lot of the information on the Counter Culture Coffee they brew and the thought that goes behind some of their policies.  He showed us a manual pour, and the cup of coffee that we tried was delicious.  He also said he would try asking customers "what size" (a complaint I had mentioned earlier) to see if he finds it to be a positive change or not.  I truly appreciated the time and effort he put into meeting with us, and it shows how much he values his customers.  I will definitely give Mugshots another chance!

**

I've been going to Mugshots for almost a year now to grade papers after work, and every once in a while, I find something off, but not really questioned it.  Today I'm convinced that something is definitely off with this coffee shop.  First, I do have to agree with some other reviewers by saying that their coffee really isn't good.  I've had it a couple times, hoping that the burnt taste was just a fluke that day.  Unfortunately, it is not.  Since then, I've just been sticking with their teas, which they do have a large selection of.  I've only had a couple of their cupcakes and bags of chips as far as food goes, and I can't complain about either.

One thing that I have never experienced in any other cafe besides Mugshots is their automatic upgrade to a medium or large drink if you don't preference what size you want....what?!?  I don't understand the logic of it.  The only explanation I can think of for this is that this is their way to make a few extra cents off each customer, and most of the time it is probably without the customer even knowing.  What audacity for the cafe to put a sign on the counter requesting customers to write a review for them on Yelp, when they do not even have the energy to say, "what size?" to each customer.  Again, I just don't get it.

Why is there a need to put a sign on every SMALL table requesting single-seaters to sit at the bar instead, before they even make that decision if the shop is too full??  It's a turn off before you even sit down.

And my final complaint - I purchased a Groupon for $15, which gave me $35 to spend on items after 4pm.  Unfortunately, in the fine print, they state that it has to be used in one visit.  Again....what?!?  I can only compare it to other coffee establishments that I've purchased deals for, and I must say that this is not the case at those places.  I can't think of a reasonable explanation for this, either.  Who really spends $35 at a cafe in one visit???  Most likely, not regular customers.  

I don't feel that Mugshots values or makes any efforts to feel like a cozy, comfortable, neighborhood coffee shop.  I will be looking for another establishment to give my business to ASAP.

Mugshots follows the age old saying...life is a series of tradeoffs.  I so want to rate them highly because they are my locally owned, B corp coffeehouse.  But the inconsistencies, though they don't make me stop coming, are frustrating.  For every pro, there's a con...

1.  The drinks.  Love the iced soy latte...bold flavor and more kick than Starbucks!  The drip coffee though...light and slightly bitter.  And the nitpicky upcharges...they even charge extra for ice.  Never seen that before at a chain or locally owned.  

2.  The food.  I love the egg sandwich on toast...very clean, but way overpriced.  Two eggs whites on two slices of bread for $5.50.  Yikes!  Add any vegs and its a dollar per.

3.  The environment.  Funky, cool, and mostly comfortable...steer clear of the pews against the wall, though.   And the couches and outdoor seating have seen better days.  Don't like kids?  Steer clear of weekend mornings...its pandemonium! 

4. The service.  Oh boy...all over the place. Some days I am treated like the loyal customer I am with memory of my order and name, and other days i am met with hipster indifference and silly mistakes like not asking if i have the loyalty card.  I think the problem is the revolving door of new people and lack of training.  For example, they recently changed register and loyalty card system...it took 6 weeks of back and forth with the owner by email to fix my account, by the end of which i was walking the counter help through how to ring up purchases.  Sad.

So, here's the insider's scoop...your chances of them doing well in all categories during your visit is 50%.  If you like those odds and the pros above outweigh the cons in your opinion, go there.  If not, OCF down the street has higher quality food at more reasonable prices, but the coffee is not as good and the environment is sterile.

Sadly, I'd love a solid Starbucks on Fairmount.  Yes they are a chain, but they train and take care of their people well, which translates to excellent service, and the food and drink are always consistent.

I typically don't frequent coffee shops, but it's good to know Mugshots is there if I ever need it. 

Gearing up for a long day, my husband and I stopped in last Saturday morning. It was before 8am and we were two of three customers in the shop on this dreadfully rainy morning. 

Knowing they had some fun bagel options, I had a little fun and picked the jalapeno bagel with goat cheese herb spread. It was like my perfect bagel flavor match. Although to be honest, it didn't really as much resemble a bagel as it did a gourmet sandwich. I thought $3.50 was a little steep of a price but needed the carb-o-load so proceeded. It wasn't super huge in size and they didn't overly schmear it.

There were two coffee options of the day and the Hologram coffee was the more appealing of the two. It had chocolate undertones and was described as the more traditional coffee option. I thought it reminded me of the fresh version of a fancy K-Cup flavor, but my husband thought it was a little too sweet. 

My husband and I planned on splitting a medium coffee but there was a misunderstanding and the barista poured us a medium and small cup. We didn't catch this until after we were wrung up. The extra charge was removed from my card and she let us keep the extra coffee anyways since it was just going to get tossed. 

I enjoyed my fancy bagel and spread, and overall we had an okay experience. I thought the bagels and coffee were overpriced, and as someone who doesn't have a usual need for a coffee shop, I can store this away into the special occasion category.  There are other places in the area to get a decent cup of coffee and a fresh-baked carb.

For delicious casual food (regular or vegan) and great coffee you can't do much better than Mugshots.

I am not loving this new location, I strongly preferred the shabby coziness of the old one - but while atmosphere is important it's more about the food and coffee and here Mugshots excels.  There hasn't been anything we've tried and didn't like, it's simply the degree of how much we like it - and the organic, locally sourced efforts they make are much appreciated.  

Sandwiches etc
We've tried many of their sandwiches and all have been good but  the "Capone (turkey, bacon, avocado wrap) and the "Bonnie and Clyde" (chicken, provolone, pesto) are a delicious blend of flavors and textures and so good.

I try to lean a bit toward eating vegan at times and they offer some yummy sandwich options - also love love LOVE their spicy vegan chili - it really has a wonderful kick.   

Desserts
They also always seem to have delicious desserts, many vegan things like cupcakes,  huge cowgirl cookies and also I had a vegan whoopie pie there once that was better than any the regular whoopie pie I have ever eaten.  The smoothies are yummy too - I especially like the Strawberry Paradise.

Breakfast
Breakfast didn't quite do it for me like other meals I've had there but maybe I've ordered the wrong things as hubby raved about the delicious bacon on his sandwich recently.  I had a bagel once that was just ok and an egg and cheese sandwich that I had a hard time seeing  or tasting whatever the cheese was, it seemed mostly just egg - if I got it again I'd ask what my cheese choices are and maybe get something else. They do have some nice (if somewhat warm) fresh squeezed OJ.  

One negative - we came at 8:30 one night (their website says open til 10 but apparently that has changed to 9) and were brusquely told "we're closing at 9!" - we heard this repeated to anyone and everyone they came in contact with and the staff started putting the stools upside down on the counter around 8:40 - I was waiting for them to start wailing out the infamous bar shut down "you don't have to go home but you can't stay here!"  - it was rather rude.

We've only been to the new location a couple of times and it seems to be all 20-somethings whereas the old location always had people of all ages - maybe it's just a weird coincidence? Or did all the older people live on the other side of Fairmount Ave and don't like to cross the street or something? I do wish they'd put in a few old couches and create some cozy little areas. In any case, we'll keep coming back (as long as it's not near 9) - we do like their coffee and food!

It's pretty nice to have Mugshots right down the block. Since I moved to the neighborhood at the beginning of this past summer, I've had three distinct experiences with this coffee shop:

Experience 1:
It was the middle of the day. It was hot outside. I had been gallivanting around Fairmount and I wanted something small to eat and also to try one of Mugshots' drinks for the first time. Since it was in the afternoon, I wasn't in the market for coffee. I walked in as a very-perplexed customer and spent a super-long time analyzing their menu.

The sweet person working answered several of my questions about their drinks and probably thought I was stupid for being so dumb re: basic coffeehouse offerings. Eventually, I decided on a Black Beauty smoothie, which tasted both sweet and healthy (blackberry, boysenberry, blueberry, and yogurt), and also a baconator bagel, whiiiich was.. not healthy. Mm.

Experience 2:
Mugshots was one of the stops on the Great Philadelphia Craft Beer Crawl last month. I did not have coffee during this visit. I had a Yards Pale Ale. It's nice that they participate in community events! They were packed that day. Aaaand that's the extent of Experience 2. Apologies that it wasn't more exciting.

Experience 3:
Tonight! They hosted a free menu tasting and fall celebration event, which equated to a generous spread of cheeses, spreads, hummus, pita, salad, flatbreads (apple butter + mushroom), and french toast. What a great way to bring people in! Standout: the apple butter flatbread. Unique, and I likely never would've thought to order that on my own!

After getting a taste of some of their delicious fall offerings, I purchased a blood orange mocha and a cranberry kale salad with organic chicken (~$15 together). The kale salad had a nice lemon-honey dressing on it and it was mixed with shaved parmesan and almonds. I'd definitely get it again. As for the blood orange mocha? Thumbs up x2. It had more of a chocolate taste than blood orange, but it was quality stuff.

I would probably frequent Mugshots more since it's super-super close to me, but I own a Keurig and I love my Keurig. Still, they do host some pretty fun events, their staff has always been very nice, and it also looks like a nice place to stay for awhile with a laptop. So far, so good.

Five years ago I was always at the old Mugshots on Fairmount to study.  Once, after cheering for my friend at the start line for the marathon, I went to Mugshots to snack and nap while I waited for him to make it to the half-way mark (no joke) and then again after the half-way to the finish (!). There would be a handful of tables and an even smaller amount of plugs for laptops so people would always be clamoring for seats. Now that Mugshots has expanded (many more locations), I was happy to see that you can get something new and something old at all the different Mugshots. 

The new one here at Fairmount is pretty spacious and has a great menu so you can hole up there for breakfast and lunch and not just be eating bagels. There's bar space where you can sit and talk to the baristas or work on you laptop, as well as tons more tables lining the walls to sit and do work. But with all these new seating (and did I mention limited outdoor seating?) the place feels... way less cozy and cool. More like a polished chain with the expensive (for a coffee shop) food and drinks. So that part is sad, but I'm hoping over time they'll get more local art up on the walls and maybe have more comfy chairs and somehow go back to make themselves more unique and interesting. What I'm trying to say is that it's waaay harder to nap at this one. But as a student, that's probably a good thing.

There are certain things in my life that I am a bit of a freak about and the source of my food is one of them. I wasn't always like this. I used to eat a 50 piece McNugget to myself on a Sunday afternoon before ordering a pizza / stromboli combo. Something happened though. I had a friend that would warn me about pesticides and GMOs and I thought he was crazy but one day I began looking into things. While I still do think he's a little crazy a lot of what he said made sense so I began researching some more.

I'm not a scientist but locally raised and grown organic food is good for the producer, the community, and the consumer. So when we went to Mugshots one Saturday after the gym and I read their chalkboard siting the source and type of all the ingredients they use (ie. So and So Farms Free Range Chicken) I got really hype. 

I ordered the breakfast burrito, mmmm..... good LAWD was it tasty. Perfect size too for an early lunch. The black beans blended with the cheese and sauce they put in it and it also had avocado sour cream on the side for dipping.

In my former life I used to eat seven McDonald's breakfast burritos in a sitting. Those are 1/4 the size of Mugshots but I swear to God I could prob have eaten 3 of these puppies.

If all you are looking for is coffee that is hot and black, I'd suggest going elsewhere.... Like WaWa or Starbucks.  For a couple bucks you can get a huge cup of some burnt tasting brown liquid brewed from the forcibly extracted souls of a bunch of spurned coffee beans picked by some poor child getting paid 2cents an hour.  

If, however, you are looking for some good caffeinated shit that you and your taste buds can feel good about - get your ass to Mugshots.  The Mugshots crew is awesome and they don't give you that "you're not hipster enough to be spending your money here" feel/look like a certain coffee shop down the street.  

Speaking of spending money, I understand that the price tends to put some people off (at least according to some of these less than stellar yelp reviews) - but think about what they are doing here.  They aren't feeding you some chemical-laden cookie or sandwich delivered to them by a Sysco truck.  They work with multiple vendors including LOCAL FARMERS ya'll to get you some fresh-ass shit while supporting people who aren't being manipulated by huge corporations.  That's a plus in my book.

Bottom line: the food, the drinks, and the atmosphere are top notch. 

***They also cater!  If you have a work event (or any party really) - order from mugshots.  But if you do, expect a sore hand from all the high fives coming your way 'cause you done made a good choice, my friend.

I have been coming here for years since they were on 21st and Fairmont and hardly realized I've never written them a proper review. 

First off I have to say that Mugshots has some of the best coffee that I have ever tried. With a large variety of roasts supplied by counter culture coffee it is always a treat trying the different varieties. My personal favorite is actually a staff recommendation: the cortado. Trust me on this one

The staff is another great aspect about Mugshots. Never have I ever received such consistently friendly service. Sometimes it is backed up but that is usually during lunch hours or breakfast when they have the most traffic. I remember when I first moved to the city and was looking for good spots to bring my date for lunch I was given a long list of great spots including a pizza shop, small French bistro, and a book store on fairmount that we ended up loosing ourselves in. 

The food has gotten phenomenal over the years especially with the inclusion of the new flat breads like the apple butter and bacon one which helped me recover after new years eve. My favorite however is the quiche and the Capone wrap which are my favorite choices for breakfast and lunch when accompanied by a coffee or smoothie. 

I'd recommend this coffee shop to my friends and keep it secret from my enemies. Keep it up Mugshots!

I simply LOVE this coffee shop. They started down the street - across the Eastern State Penitentiary - and are now between 19 and 20 on Fairmount Ave. The quality of the coffee is what always brings me back here (yes, it is AWESOME!). Featuring Counter Culture Coffees is what does it! The coffee and espresso drinks never cease to be enjoyable. And their friendly staff know how to talk about coffee without coming across as condescending. Plus the drinks are always beautifully presented. (By the way try their traditional cappuccino; it is amazing!!) Over the past few months they have also started to carry a couple of other brands of coffee as well (Yay, for starting to carry ReAnimator!!!) which makes this a happily unusually shop in the coffee industry. I highly suggest stopping in and asking one of the baristas to do a pourover for you, they will let you choose any coffee that is for sale! 

On a final note, the menu here is amazing! The overwhelming selection of food makes it the perfect place to stop in and grab a bite.  And if you are  vegetarian, vegan or gluten-free... no worries. They have the options to suite your dietary needs (even in the realm of deserts). Definitely try their Vegan Espresso Brownies; they are to die for!

Mugshots....where to start? Well I'm a coffee shop snob-I get that-I've worked/met/held court in/avoided work in coffee shops from Philadelphia to San Francisco so I have a few things that for me are non-negotiable when it comes to a neighborhood cafe. I have zero tolerance for pretention when it comes to ambiance and staffing. I want just plain coffee and I want it to be really really good. I want there to be food that is inventive, well executed, healthy, local, and I want options. I want enough space that I don't feel guilty for sitting down for more than 5min. Everything else is negotiable. Mugshots delivers in all categories-to the point that I have given up making my daily cup at home and driving there every morning before work to get an excellent cup of hot or iced and to have my favorite baristas (Garrett and Rose you complete me) remember what I want, how I want it, and keep me up to date with the local hijinks. I take everyone who comes into town there-my brother who lives in Singapore insists on stopping in Philadelphia expressly to spend an hour or two relaxing and drinking regular drip (which is apparently impossible to get anywhere that isn't the States). Go. You'll see what I mean.

Came by for the first time Sunday at 9AM after reading many positive reviews. Staff wasn't really friendly as many people put in their reviews. Coffee was light and not much taste. I ordered a latte and an iced hazelnut coffee. Decided to give them another chance, came back this morning at 7AM ordered an iced coffee, staff wasn't friendly, they were chit chatting among themselves instead of focusing on the customer. My iced hazelnut coffee wasn't come out the way I expected like Sunday. I was confused and then the guy asked me "you ordered iced coffee right? Here is the milk would you like me pour it for you?" It was all black. I guess I was expecting the same iced hazelnut coffee as  I ordered Sunday. Same order two different day and time came out differently. I gave them a second chance. Not going back. There are many other good one out there. Their coffee is not good they are just in a great location with a nice shop.

Walked in and went to order a coffee, the cashier jumped as if I yelled at her when I said "Excuse me ma'am." Tried to order a sandwich a while back, 35 minutes later I go back to a different cashier, he asked about the exact sandwich I ordered and instead of serving me or apologizing he just asked me if I wanted my money back. No explanation as to why the sandwich was never made. 

I was also the only Black person in the spot.

This place is awful. I went in yesterday a small vanilla late cots 6.50 when I asked the worker why it's costs so much he got very snappy with me and said he doesn't make the prices. I said a latte at Starbucks does not cost this much. He rudely said fine go to Starbucks. To say the least I left and did not pay for the drink nor will I ever be back!

I genuinely believe I'm not wanted here despite having stopped in a number of times. If I order an iced coffee, and then get charged for, and given an iced americano one more time, I'm going to do nothing except for continue my Volo boycott.

I have been a regular here for many years, stopping in at least once weekly for a cappuccino and maybe a sandwich or something, which is usually all very good. However, I have some real problems with this place that just seem to be getting worse. First of all, this place needs a good scrub down and update. The floors are dusty and filthy and the tables and chairs look like clawed cats have lived on them for quite some time. Also, while most of the baristas are very friendly like the guy with the long hair and all of the girls, there's one guy with a mustache and a beanie who is consistently rude. The issue is that he is almost always there, so unfortunately I must avoid this coffee shop if I'm not in the mood to have a rude encounter. Also, there is no designated area to put your dirty dishes, so after you're done with your coffee and/or food you're left with the daunting task of deliberating over whether you should leave your dishes on the table, or place them on the same bar that other people are being served their coffee on, which I think is gross. But, the guy with the mustache gives me attitude if I leave my stuff on the table, so unless I want a nasty stink eye and a passive aggressive comment the next time I come in I am obligated to carry my dishes across the shop and place them beside someone's fresh coffee. Kinda makes me feel like a kid who got in trouble on the playground...not what I came for. Also, new employees should be trained before opening or after closing as opposed to serving customers sub-par coffee all day until they've got it right. I personally don't want to pay four dollars for coffee that's just okay. Otherwise, the sandwiches, bagels, salads, and yogurt were consistently quite good, but they often ran out of pastries or only had little brioches left or something a little old and stale that just wouldn't hit the spot. Ultimately, I don't think I'll be back. Good coffee and food doesn't cut it for me when the rest of my experience is too often simply not enjoyable.

Issue#1: Animals in cafe. Customers bring dogs into the cafe. Today the barista walked around the counter and pet a customers small hairy dog for a few mins, kissing it etc. Then goes back to making drinks. If you are allergic to animals or have taken college biology you know how offensive that is on so many levels. 

Issue#2: Internet, outlets and noise. Internet is on and off, dropping out every few mins. No Outlets for laptops. NONE. And way to noisey, braistas take pride in banging the espresso handles and the acoustics of the place amplify the sound. I don't expect a library, but the noise here is noticeably annoying. This place needs a make over...yesterday. Need a new bar, some outlets and better lighting.  

Issue#3: Offerings. Coffee is reasonably priced $2.50 with $0.50 cent refills, but its way too strong (almost sludge status). Its not bad...just not for light roasted drinkers. My friend who likes dark roast, loved his coffee. Pastries are unreasonably expensive. Rock hard, ok tasting biscotti for $2. $3 for a tart etc. Have not tried sandwiches but after seeing the staff pet the dog, I will pass on the food.  

Staff is nice, but kinda aloof. No small talk, usually on their phones or straight to the point. The crowd here is older regulars and well heeled locals. In summer with windows open it is a nice place to hang and have a conversation. But if you need to read or get work done, head to sbux alcove down the block.

I've been stopping here for years since it's previous incarnation.  The current operation does not come close to it's predecessor.  The espresso shots are tight and short.  I mean $2.50 for a one ounce, down the hatch in seconds shot that is pulled according to the very know-it-all barista for 18 seconds (or less).  That's nonsense, and when I told him so, he told me his boss would get mad if he pulled a longer shot!  His Boss!  I'm the customer, and if I think a thimbleful of espresso is too tight, loosen the grip.  So then he proceeds to ask if I wanted him to add more to my cup.  You can't do that, and he knows it.  So he pulls a second shot, and this one is about and ounce and a half.  When he sees that I'm not happy, he proceeds, even though I'm telling him never mind, to make a third, obviously over extracted shot of mediocre espresso.  All the while telling me that he's, "read books on espresso."  When I tell him I have a $1000 setup at home, he starts asking me questions about it as if to make sure I'm giving him the truth.  Sorry, this isn't the first time I've encountered this guy, and he needs to remember that the customer is king. "Don't like your shot?  Let me fix it."  Skip the lecture.

Coffee is four stars, service earns one star (maybe less). Case in point: this morning, I go in to order a latte. Barrista is busy talking to owner, but breaks away and stands at the counter. I say good morning with a smile, but all little mister Andy Warhol wannabe can muster is a deadpan stare, so I mumble my order, get my drink, and get the hell out. Owner stood by as all this occurred, so I doubt this poor service experience strays from the norm. Thoroughly unimpressed with the attitude at this joint. Come on Volo, you can do better than this.

I have been here a few times and I have always enjoyed the coffee. 

Coffee: Always has been good! There aren't a myriad of options, but you know when the menu isn't full of craziness, the quality is really the thing to enjoy. I think the prices are reasonable and not overly ridiculous. When is a great coffee place super cheap? Never! I can't comment on the food- never had it, but it always sounds delish :)

Staff & Service: As one yelper mentioned- unpretentious! They are always so nice, kind and cool. It's a hipster/laid back/ chill vibe. They always seem really cool- like "ooo I could be his/her friend!"

Atmosphere: This is where I feel like the shop falls a LITTLE short. I like my coffee places where it's warm and snuggly- this place doesn't give me that vibe at all. I'd much prefer to come here over the summer vs. winter. For me it's not an ideal place to post-up and study, there aren't too many tables and the place lacks in outlets to charge. Volvo isn't big and there are no comfy big chairs/couches, only wooden chairs & tables. Mainly 2-person tables. There is lots of great lighting, but because the place is so small, whenever the door opens it sometimes gets pretty chilly. I kept my coat on most of the time. In the summer there are fun places to sit outside and it is a good place to get a coffee with a friend or two and talk. Just not really study place (limited room, not the warm snuggly atmosphere I like). 

Parking: There is metered street, but if you go on the side streets for free, you can find a place as long as you are ok with walking a few blocks to get there.

Overall- I know I'll be back, I am giving 3 stars based on the atmosphere part.

Had to meet someone here for a work meeting and was excited to try a new coffeehouse. Found street parking in front (it was a Tuesday morning) and was charmed by the high ceilings and light interior. Loved the decor. Ordered a large soy vanilla latte with an extra espresso shot (total of 4 shots), and a toasted multigrain bagel with butter. The latte was ok. Nothing special but perfectly fine. I love strong lattes, and It didn't taste like it had four shots of espresso, but it was ok. 

The bagel however, was just plain bad. Awful. Had zero flavor. The butter added some much-needed saltiness but it was possibly the most bland multigrain bagel I've had in a very long time. I wasn't going to complain to the staff about a measly bagel but I won't ever be ordering it again. Hard to know if their other food is prepared as blandly. Hopefully it's just the brand of bagel they use. Probably should have ordered a pastry instead. 

I rarely go to Manyunk so I'm not sure if and when I'd return here. It's always a great addition to a neighborhood to have a coffeehouse, so I'm glad it's there. But I wouldn't go here expecting a unique or masterful coffee or food experience.

This place would get a 4-5 typically but I have had customer service related beefs.  First off the coffee is friggn awesome, I think they really care about every cup they make and there isn't one item I could complain about.  Second, you get the feeling the crowd is a little more put together then the ones that go to the chain coffee shop down the street (I go to both, depends on my mood, parking, and how much time I want to spend)..sometimes it feels a little elitist or pretentious in here, admittingly I'm looking for that sometimes.  The customer service beef i have is that it takes FOREVER to pay for something, the other reason is a one time incident but left a bad taste in my mouth...and has given me mixed feelings about going in... sitting in the car outside of Volo a few min early one day and a woman with a baby in her stroller tried to open the door, the two people in there looked at her and totally ignored her!  (Dude with the glasses).  It was like 3 min until opening.  The woman looked at them and walked away.  I hung a Uturn and went to the lower brow down the street...my conscious felt better but my taste buds suffered.

I was in the area meeting with friends who just moved to Manyunk and did not know of any good places yet for coffee/breakfast. From the reviews on Yelp, I was excited to try this place. From one of the reviews, someone rated highly the egg sandwich (panini bread, egg, spinach, cheese and pancetta). This was very good and quite filling. It was a real egg and not one from the freezer or that you would get at Starbucks or Dunkin Donuts. I was disappointed with the iced mocha that I got. It tasted just like milk. I couldn't taste any espresso. I didn't want to go back to the counter as the line was out the door (which is a good thing but not for me at that point). It was $5 and not worth it. My friend ordered a hot chocolate and the barista was nice enough to let her know that they use bittersweet chocolate so they would sweeten it to her liking. She was not thrilled. I would go back for the ambiance and even the egg sandwich again but I am skeptical about other drinks.

Volo cup, I fill you up.

My husband and I were walking around the Manayunk area one Saturday in late August, looking for a coffee shop other than Starbucks and voila - Volo appeared.  Apparently it's so popular that it's difficult to find seating.  We walked around a little more and then returned 30 minutes later to snag a perfect two-person table.  The atmosphere is quite modern and open, not like your warm neighborhood Starbucks, so it depends on the vibe you want.  Because it's one, fairly small open room, it did get rather noisy - particularly when a poor dishwasher smashed an entire tray of dishes on the floor.  I'm able to tune out the background noise, while my husband is not - so know you're party's preferences.  I appreciated that they had a surge protector near a cluster of tables so that more than two people could charge their laptops; mine has a gimpy battery that dies after fifteen minutes without electricity, so I factor outlets into my coffee shop assessments.  If you don't need an outlet, you can sit outside when the weather's nice and people watch while you sip your drink of choice.

But the coffee - oh wow.  I ordered a small half-caf iced coffee, and my husband got a hot vanilla latte in a mug.  The cashier was nice when I asked if they could make it half-caf, even though I know coffee snobs turn their nose up at that - but he probably saw my pregnant belly.  We paid $7-$8, which is a little steep for liquid calories, but it was worth the taste.  We only waited three minutes, despite the volume of customers.  The latte came out first, and it was beautifully topped with swirled, decorated foam.  It wasn't too sweet, but you could still taste the vanilla - a lovely balance.  The barista serving my iced coffee made sure to say "half-caf" with a nice smile, which reassured me that they had made it properly.  I added cream and sugar (I only add sugar to my iced coffee, okay?!) at the bar from a cute little tray they provide.  I only wish they had two trays on busy days or at high volume times, because I had to ask the woman next to me who was waiting for her coffee to make room so I could reach the cream.  

We didn't order any food, since we'd just had lunch, but I would love to go back and try their food.  They had a three-cheese grilled cheese that sounded really good, and the salads on another ladies' table looked sizable.  I'd say there were about five-six sandwiches, three-four salads, maybe a soup, and several baked goods on the menu.  A co-worker tells me that their multi-grain bagels slathered with butter are the best he's had, and he's a Philly native.  Actually, a couple of my co-workers come into work most mornings with a cup of Volo joe, despite our office providing very good coffee.

Great coffee, decent value, distinct atmosphere, located in the heart of walkable Manayunk.

Perhaps I'm crazy, but whenever I review a coffee shop I have only one simple criteria when it comes to product, one simple test I run: give me a cup of black coffee. When all you have is a simple cup, without milk, sugar, foams and flavor extracts there is no room to hide anything. All that will matter is where the beans are from, what the roaster did to them, and whether the water was high quality and at the proper temperature. Nothing else. I cannot tell you how many times I've gone into a trendy coffee shop and walked away disappointed because the product is lackluster.

Volo surpasses that test, and does it in spades. Their house blend is a bit lighter than I usually like ( I typically am a fan of dark, DARK roasts) but they managed to get a very nice amount of flavor, with low astringency and I'm convinced that I need to try their espresso. (which is my secondary test) While they are not particularly my wheelhouse, the last time I visited my companion had a green tea latte which was artfully prepared, and considered tasty.

The décor it great as well, as the large windows in the front give the location plenty of light and the high ceilings prevent you from feeling claustrophobic. The art scattered around gave plenty to provide some excitement to the walls and the staff was relatively friendly. Overall, I say they're worth a trip.

Came to Volo for the first time ever last weekend in order to take refuge from the house-hunting I had been doing. And i am glad I did! While certainly hipster in appearance and vibe, this place serves delicious coffee right on Main Street  in manayunk. 

The classic cappuccino I ordered and happily consumed was just what I needed to reset myself. The dessert/pastry options looked great so I asked the barista where they got them from. She actually wasn't sure which was sort of a bummer. As a future manayunk resident relocating from Baltimore (also known as smalltimore), I'm used to local small businesses teaming up with other local small businesses to offer complementary products. Since there were two bakeries across the street from Volo, I was hoping to hear they got their goods from one of them. Oh well, still some great coffee to be had there.

We were wandering down Main Street looking for coffee to grab before heading to brunch at Le Bus when we lucked out and found this great little coffee shop. It was 10:15 on a Sunday morning and we didn't have to wait in line for coffee?!?! Us Center City dwellers did not understand this but we liked it very much. We ordered a Latte and a House Coffee and were very satisfied when we realized that they brewed La Columbe coffee. We'd much rather patronize a coffeehouse like Volo over the Starbucks and other chains in the city. You could tell the baristas took pride in their work and they were speedy, helpful, and nice. There is plenty of tables to sit down if you are looking to relax with a friend or come here to get some work done. If you are ever are in search of a good coffee experience in Manayunk, check this place out.

This is by far my favorite and most nostalgic place in Philadelphia.  I will get the important stuff out of the way first:

BEST COFFEE I HAVE HAD IN THE UNITED STATES

BEST ICED COFFEE IVE EVER HAD (not to mention price)

BEST PANINI IVE EVER HAD (classic)

ONE OF THE BEST SALADS (salmon)

GREATEST ATMOSPHERE EVER AT A COFFEE SHOP

Okay if you're still with me here are the deets.  I was a regular here from 2004-2008 while I was in school.  Back then it was La Colombe, The LC.  This was my stop.  I wasn't overrun by classmates.  I could stay for 8 hours and not feel like a jerk.  I had my little spot, next to Charlie's table, in the corner just by the door.  8-Noon was a Cappuccino.  Noon-4 was a Classic Panini and an Iced Coffee.  On nice days I'd grab a table on the sidewalk for the best outdoor seating spot in Philly.  It really is perfect.  

Years later I still stopped by whenever I went to Manayunk.  It was literally like visiting my parents house.  Everyone there has always been super nice and really fun.  There are a lot of artists in Manayunk so you'd see them stop buy for breaks.  The window-wash guy alway came buy and had a chat.  The aforementioned icon Charlie was maybe the greatest guy in the world.  It just always felt right.

Back then LC downtown was known for being the European coffee shop because you walked into a wall of smoke and it was so busy it had the sense of gruffness that comes with high traffic.  It had it's own appeal.  But LC/Volo has always been a little bit of Paris.  Clean, quiet, awesome music, GREAT COFFEE, great people.  

When I got married we served La Colombe coffee at our wedding.  Even today living in SF we have it shipped every month.  It's just the best on so many levels.  

If life is so busy you can only grab and go still come by-- it's also the cheapest coffee in town.  But if you can, preferably on a weekday, stop in around 10am and stay until you nip off somewhere for happy hour around closing.  Bring a good book, maybe some music (unless Tenzen is still there jamming radiohead), and get comfy.  Over the course of the day you'll see the waves of people come by like episodes in a show-- the cyclists clicking around (they always know where the good coffee is), the artists getting the day started at 1pm, the moms bringing the kids in after school for a hot chocolate, the after work crowd swinging in to grab a seat outside to let some stress melt away (that's how I ran into Darren Aronofsky, Shane Victorino, and the better part of the CSC racing team!). 

I can't explain it in any other way than to say that is just fun, it's always fun and feels right.  It's almost like it shouldn't exist in America.  Sure the coffee's great, sure it's a unique spot in the world of franchised coffees hops.  But if you really want to enjoy it, to see why it's still run by the same awesome guy all this time and the same people come in every day, come in and stay a while.

I came here to meet with Tonya M., a lady I met on an online dating site (OK Cupid). I went on one online date already, the first time I tried to get out there and meet people after the end of my 14-year marriage with my ex-wife (Cynthia). She now lives with our twin sons (Bradley and Bryan) in Glenside. 

I was pretty scared to go on another online date, since the first one fizzled out. But I figured I would try again after Tonya M. reached out to me. It seemed like we had a lot of similar interests. She said that she liked to read and I at one point thought about maybe writing professionally before deciding upon a career as an actuary. I currently develop risk valuation models for parking garages across North America (our company works with a firm with Canadian assets). 

It went really well with Tonya M. I was up front and told her about the divorce with Cynthia, how much of it was my fault because I hid behind my career due to my fears of being a husband and father. My own dad was TERRIFIC and was always there for me and imparted many valuable life lessons. I never thought I would live up to his standards and I ended up not doing so. (There is hurt on both sides of the split, however.)

Tonya M. understood quite a bit and said that we all make mistakes. She confessed to me something she didn't put in her profile -- she was starting her life over, too. 

She had spent a little under two years in jail for voter fraud. 

Tonya M. and I had an enjoyable conversation and have left the possibilities open for a second date elsewhere in Northwest Philadelphia. I'm not sure how I feel about dating a woman with a police record, but like she said, we all make mistakes. Also, it was a white-collar crime done at the behest of her then-boss. 

Volo Coffeehouse was TERRIFIC. Just great coffee and a wonderful atmosphere right on Main Street. It was cozy (and had a lot of bike riders) but still a great place.

I would recommend Volo Coffeehouse to anyone in Philadelphia who is going on an OK Cupid date with a woman who has committed voter fraud in an attempt to rig a suburban school board election.

I love Volo!!! Used to be a la colombe, which is a world cllass coffee roaster. The owner retained the original elements and simply changed name.  HUGE windows to look out of while sipping coffee or tea.  Well thought out panini and salads. I hesitate to discuss the pastry selection because it's nearly as addicting as the coffee, pssttt...raisin danish is 5 stars.

Workers can handle the massive line in the morning so don't worry they'll set up your order faster than you think.

Don't expect to order crazy fraps and syrups because they focus on the coffee old school. Drip coffee, cappuccino, latte and espresso are my favorites.

The neighborhood is very nice for grabbing to go and walking around.

Also, usually, there is a table of folks that meet in the morning. They are very friendly and asked me to join them to talk about general topics.  Stuff like this is rare and shows the place a great vibe.

They really try to relate to the community with take one/leave one books and 
cork board with everything from dog sitting, babysitting, apartment rentals and local shows.

I visit about 3-4 times per week on my way to the city. 

0 stars, I give 5 galaxies!

Wow did I love this place. Food and vibe, both perfect. I went Saturday looking for a really good iced soy chai (a favorite of mine) and brought a book. This place had that perfect grab something delicious, get lost in what you're doing or who you're with vibe. It helped that it was raining outside, very seattle :) I grabbed a tea and a recommended almond croissant-YUM, a must get without a doubt- sat down to read and didnt leave for hours.
Came back Sunday with a friend, much more packed at exactly the same time so be aware Sundays are brutal! The latte may be one of the best I have ever had. I may have to start hiking it over here before work in the mornings. And of course I grabbed another almond croissant! although the cinnamon roll and the apple tart were both calling my name...
Be aware, it is a small place, Any more than two people will be tought to find a table. And you may not get a seat. But if you have the time to wait for one to open instead of grabbing your coffee in a to-go cup, do it.
